---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import CapitalGainsTaxCalculator from "../../components/CapitalGainsTaxCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Capital Gains Tax Calculator (US) | Estimate Your Tax Liability"
  description="Free capital gains tax calculator for the US. Estimate short-term and long-term tax rates, including the Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT)."
>
  <main class="flex-grow pt-24 pb-20">
    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        Capital Gains Tax Calculator (United States)
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Model your potential tax liability on the sale of assets like stocks, real estate, or crypto under IRS rules.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <CapitalGainsTaxCalculator defaultCountry="US" />
    </div>

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16 px-4">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-emerald-500/10 text-emerald-400 border border-emerald-500/20 mb-4">Tax Strategy (United States)</span>
            <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight leading-snug">
              Understanding US Capital Gains Tax
            </h2>
          </div>

          <div class="space-y-8 text-sm text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Introduction</h3>
              <p>
                In the United States, the IRS taxes your profits from the sale of an asset. The rate you pay depends heavily on how long you held the asset before selling it. This calculator helps you estimate your potential tax liability based on the latest IRS rules.
              </p>
              <p class="mt-2">
                For a comprehensive guide on minimizing these taxes, check out our <a href="/blog/capital-gains-tax-us/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">US Capital Gains Tax Guide</a>.
              </p>
            </article>

            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Key Concepts</h3>
              <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
                <li><strong>Short-term capital gains:</strong> Assets held for 1 year or less are taxed as ordinary income, which can be up to 37%.</li>
                <li><strong>Long-term capital gains:</strong> Assets held for more than 1 year benefit from preferential tax rates of 0%, 15%, or 20% depending on your filing status and taxable income.</li>
                <li><strong>Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT):</strong> High earners may also be subject to an additional 3.8% tax on investment income above certain thresholds (e.g., $200,000 for Single filers).</li>
              </ul>
            </article>
            
            <article>
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-3">Methodology</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator determines your taxable gain by subtracting your purchase price from the sale amount. It then applies either the short-term ordinary income tax brackets or the long-term preferential rates based on your holding period. For high earners, it automatically calculates the 3.8% NIIT if your total income exceeds the IRS thresholds for your filing status.
              </p>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 italic mt-4">
                Source: <a href="https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc409" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="hover:text-slate-300 underline">IRS Topic No. 409 Capital Gains and Losses</a>.
              </p>
            </article>
          </div>

          <!-- FAQ Accordion -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <span class="inline-flex items-center px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest bg-amber-500/10 text-amber-400 border border-amber-500/20 mb-4">FAQ</span>
            <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h3>

            <div class="space-y-4">
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">How is long-term capital gains tax calculated in the US?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  Long-term capital gains apply to assets held longer than one year. The profit is taxed at 0%, 15%, or 20% based on your filing status and taxable income for the year.
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-slate-800 rounded-lg overflow-hidden bg-slate-900/50">
                <button class="w-full flex items-center justify-between px-6 py-5 text-left group cursor-pointer" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.classList.toggle('hidden'); this.querySelector('svg').classList.toggle('rotate-180');">
                  <span class="font-semibold text-white">What is the Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT)?</span>
                  <svg class="h-5 w-5 text-slate-500 transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg>
                </button>
                <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6 text-sm text-slate-400">
                  The NIIT is a 3.8% surcharge on investment income for individuals whose modified adjusted gross income exceeds certain thresholds ($200,000 for Single, $250,000 for Married Filing Jointly).
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Internal Links -->
          <div class="mt-12 border-t border-slate-800/80 pt-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Related Calculators</h3>
            <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
              <a href="/tax-loss-harvesting-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Tax Loss Harvesting Calculator</a>
              <a href="/buy-borrow-die-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Buy, Borrow, Die Strategy Calculator</a>
              <a href="/roth-conversion-calculator/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Roth Conversion Calculator</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is long-term capital gains tax calculated in the US?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Long-term capital gains apply to assets held longer than one year. The profit is taxed at 0%, 15%, or 20% based on your filing status and taxable income for the year."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT)?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The NIIT is a 3.8% surcharge on investment income for individuals whose modified adjusted gross income exceeds certain thresholds ($200,000 for Single, $250,000 for Married Filing Jointly)."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>
</Layout>
